triate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's footballers in Spain]]\n\n\n{{EquatorialGuinea-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pachu_(footballer,_born_1986)"}
{"title_page": "G\u00e9rard Mourou", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = G\u00e9rard Mourou\n| image = Ecole polytechnique (44330870254).jpg\n| birth_name = G\u00e9rard Albert Mourou\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1944|6|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Albertville]], [[France]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| education = [[Universit\u00e9 Grenoble Alpes|University of Grenoble]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BSc]], [[Master of Science|MSc]])}}<br />[[Pierre and Marie Curie University]] {{small|([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n| thesis_title = \n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = \n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = [[Donna Strickland]]\n| notable_students = \n| known_for = [[Chirped pulse amplification]]\n| awards = [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] {{small|(2018)}}\n| workplaces = [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique|\u00c9cole polytechnique]]<br />[[ENSTA ParisTech]]<br />[[University of Rochester]]<br />[[University of Michigan]]\n}}\n\n'''G\u00e9rard Albert Mourou''' ({{IPA-fr|\u0292e\u0281a\u0281 mu\u0281u|lang}}; born 22 June 1944)<ref name=\"Lindinger\">{{cite news |last=Lindinger |first=Manfred |date=2 October 2018 |title=Eine Zange aus lauter Licht |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wissen/nobelpreise/physik-nobelpreis-2018-praezisionswerkzeuge-aus-laserlicht-15818493.html |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |language=German |accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Nobel\">{{cite web |date=5 October 2018 |title=G\u00e9rard Mourou \u2013 Facts \u2013 2018 |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/2018/mourou/facts/ |work=NobelPrize.org |publisher=Nobel Media AB |accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> is a French scientist and pioneer in the field of [[electrical engineering]] and [[lasers]].  He was awarded a [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] in 2018, along with [[Donna Strickland]], for the invention of [[chirped pulse amplification]], a technique later used to create ultrashort-pulse, very high-intensity ([[petawatt]]) laser pulses.<ref name=Michigan_Profile>{{cite web |url=http://www.engin.umich.edu/research/cuos/ResearchGroups/HFS/Profiles/Gerard_Mourou.html |title=G\u00e9rard Mourou |last= |first= |date=2 October 2018 |website= |publisher=University of Michigan | access-date = |quote=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905085848/http://www.engin.umich.edu/research/cuos/ResearchGroups/HFS/Profiles/Gerard_Mourou.html |archive-date=5 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Mourou and his team at the [[University of Michigan]] discovered that the balance between the self-focusing refraction (see [[Kerr effect]]) and self-attenuating [[diffraction]] by [[ionization]] and rarefaction of a laser beam of terawatt intensities in the atmosphere creates \"filaments\" which act as [[waveguide]]s for the beam thus preventing divergence.\n\n==Career==\nMourou has been director of the Laboratoire d'optique appliqu\u00e9e at the [[ENSTA]] from 2005 to 2009. He is a professor and member of Haut Coll\u00e8ge at the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique|\u00c9cole polytechnique]] and A. D. Moore Distinguished University Professor Emeritus at the [[University of Michigan]] where he has taught for over 16 years. He was the founding director of the Center for Ultrafast Optical Science at the University of Michigan in 1990. He had previously led a research group on ultrafast sciences at Laboratoire d'optique appliqu\u00e9e of ENSTA and \u00c9cole polytechnique, after obtaining a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degree from [[Pierre and Marie Curie University]] in 1973. He then went to the United States and became a professor at the [[University of Rochester]] in 1977, where he and his then student [[Donna Strickland]] produced their Nobel prize-winning work in the [[Laboratory for Laser Energetics]] at the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochester.edu/newscenter/rochesters-breakthrough-in-laser-science-earns-nobel-prize-340302/ |title=Rochester breakthrough in laser science earns Nobel Prize |date=2 October 2018 |website=University of Rochester |accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref> The pair co-invented [[chirped pulse amplification]], a \"method of generating high-intensity, ultra-short optical pulses\".<ref name=\"bbc2\">{{cite news |last1=Murphy |first1=Jessica |title=Donna Strickland: The 'laser jock' Nobel prize winner |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45722890 |accessdate=2 October 2018 |publisher=BBC News |date=2 October 2018}}</ref> Strickland's doctoral thesis was on \"development of an ultra-bright laser and an application to multi-photon ionization\".<ref name=\"Thesis\">{{cite thesis |last=Strickland |first=Donna Theo |author-link=Donna Strickland |date=1988 |title=Development of an ultra-bright laser and an application to multi-photon ionization |type=PhD |publisher=University of Rochester |url=http://www.lle.rochester.edu/media/publications/documents/theses/Strickland.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707150743/http://www.lle.rochester.edu/media/publications/documents/theses/Strickland.pdf |archive-date=7 July 2013 |accessdate=6 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2000s, Mourou was featured by a French film company in a publicity video for the [[Extreme Light Infrastructure]] (ELI).<ref name=\"LeMonde\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/sciences/article/2018/10/02/quand-le-nobel-gerard-mourou-se-mettait-en-scene-dans-un-clip-musical-potache_5363583_1650684.html |title=Quand le Nobel G\u00e9rard Mourou se mettait en sc\u00e8ne dans un clip musical potache |last=Morin |first=Herv\u00e9 |work=Le Monde |quote=Le laboratoire avait contact\u00e9 une compagnie de th\u00e9\u00e2tre sp\u00e9cialis\u00e9e dans les sujets scientifiques..en 2008. C\u2019est \u00e0 cette occasion que <nowiki>[r\u00e9alisateur]</nowiki> Mokaddem Djemel a rencontr\u00e9 les chercheurs. De fil en aiguille, l\u2019id\u00e9e d\u2019une vid\u00e9o a germ\u00e9, utilisant une chanson du spectacle. (The lab contacted a theatre company specializing in scientific subjects..in 2008. It was then that <nowiki>[filmmaker]</nowiki> Mokaddem Djemel met the researchers. Gradually, the idea of a video was born, using a song from the show.) |date=2 October 2018 |accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Have you seen ELI3 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k6i7A8Plqb8 |last=|access-date=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 November 2015, he attended the Third Christmas Lecture held in Bucharest. His presentation was entitled ''Breaking Through The Unknown: Extreme light, Science to Art''. The previous lectures were given by Sir [[Thomas Kibble]] and [[Joseph Silk]].\n\n=== Nobel Prize ===\n[[File:Ecole polytechnique (31183345568).jpg|thumb|262px|Mourou, speaking in 2018 after being awarded the Nobel Prize]]\nOn 2 October 2018, Mourou and [[Donna Strickland|Strickland]] were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics, along with  for their joint work on [[chirped pulse amplification]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/oct/02/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-win-nobel-physics-prize |title=Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland win Nobel physics prize |first=Ian |last=Sample |date=2 October 2018 |journal=The Guardian |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> They shared half of the Prize, while the other half was awarded to [[Arthur Ashkin]] for his invention of \"optical tweezers that grab particles, atoms, viruses and other living cells with their laser beam fingers\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/arthur-ashkin-2-others-win-nobel-physics-prize-for-laser-research/ |title=Arthur Ashkin, 2 others win Nobel Physics Prize for laser research |date=2 October 2018 |website=Times of Israel |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"physicsworld.com\">{{cite web |url=https://physicsworld.com/a/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-the-nobel-prize-for-physics/ |title=Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland win the Nobel Prize for Physics \u2013 Physics World |date=2 October 2018 |publisher= |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:G\u00e9rard Mourou EM1B5793 (46234161551).jpg|thumb|262px|G\u00e9rard Mourou during Nobel press conference in Stockholm, December 2018]]\n\nMourou and Strickland found that stretching a laser out reduced its peak power, which could then be greatly amplified using normal instruments.\nIt could then be compressed to create the short-lived, highly powerful lasers they were after.<ref name=\"physicsworld.com\" /> The technique, which was described in Strickland's first scientific publication, came to be known as chirped pulse amplification (CPA). They were probably unaware at the time that their tools would make it possible to study natural phenomena in unprecedented ways.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://physicsworld.com/a/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-the-nobel-prize-for-physics/ |title=Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland win the Nobel Prize for Physics |first= |last= |date=2 October 2018 |publisher= |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> CPA could also per definition be used to create a laser pulse that only lasts one attosecond, one-billionth of a billionth of a second. At those timescales, it became possible not only to study chemical reactions, but what happens inside individual atoms.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' and [[Scientific American]] provided simplified summaries of the work of Strickland and Mourou: it \"paved the way for the shortest, most intense laser beams ever created\". \"The ultrabrief, ultrasharp beams can be used to make extremely precise cuts so their technique is now used in laser machining and enables doctors to perform millions of corrective\" [[laser eye surgery|laser eye surgeries]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Physics Nobel prize won by Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/oct/02/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-win-nobel-physics-prize |accessdate=2 October 2018 |publisher=The Guardian |date=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title='Optical Tweezers' and Tools Used for Laser Eye Surgery Snag Physics Nobel |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/optical-tweezers-and-tools-used-for-laser-eye-surgery-snag-physics-nobel1/ |accessdate=2 October 2018 |publisher=Scientific American |date=2 October 2018}}</ref> Canadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] acknowledged the achievements of Mourou and Strickland: \"Their innovative work can be found in applications including corrective eye surgery, and is expected to have a significant impact on cancer therapy and other physics research in the future\".<ref>[https://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2018/10/02/statement-prime-minister-donna-strickland-winning-nobel-prize-physics Statement by the Prime Minister on Donna Strickland winning the Nobel Prize in Physics 2 October 2018 PMO]</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*1995 \u2013 R. W. Wood Prize by the [[Optical Society of America|OSA]]<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.osa.org/en-us/awards_and_grants/awards/award_description/rwwood/\n | title =R. W. Wood Prize\n | date =\n | website =\n | publisher =The Optical Society\n | access-date =\n | quote =For contributions to the field of ultrafast optics, in particular for introducing the concept of chirped pulse amplification for laser systems to boost optical power peaks to unprecedented levels  }}</ref>\n*1997 \u2013 SPIE Harold E. Edgerton Award<ref name=\"SPIE\">{{cite web |title=SPIE Harold E. Edgerton Award in High-Speed Optics |url=http://spie.org/about-spie/awards-programs/current-award-winners/spie-harold-e-edgerton-award-in-high-speed-optics?SSO=1 |website=spie.org |publisher=International Society for Optics and Photonics |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n*2004 \u2013 IEEE LEOS [[IEEE Photonics Society|Quantum Electronics Award]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.photonicssociety.org/awards/quantum-electronics-award/quantum-electronics-award-award-winners |title=Quantum Electronics Award Winners |website=IEEE Photonics Society |accessdate=2 October 2018|quote=For pioneering contributions to ultrafast optics including optical sampling and intense fs pulses}}</ref>\n*2005 \u2013 Willis E. Lamb Award for Laser Science and Quantum Optics<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambaward.org/2005/2005-mourou.html |title=G\u00e9rard Mourou \u2013 the 2005 Willis E. Lamb Award for Laser Science and Quantum Optics |website=www.lambaward.org |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n*2009 \u2013 [[Charles Hard Townes Award]] by the [[Optical Society of America|OSA]]<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.osa.org/en-us/history/biographies/gerard-mourou/\n | title =G\u00e9rard Mourou\n | date =\n | website =\n | publisher =The Optical Society\n | access-date =2018-10-12\n | quote = }}</ref>\n* 2016 \u2013 [[Frederic Ives Medal]]<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.polytechnique.edu/en/content/gerard-mourou-receives-frederic-ives-medal-optical-society-america\n | title =G\u00e9rard Mourou receives the Frederic Ives Medal of the Optical Society of America\n | date =March 30, 2016\n | website =\n | publisher =\u00c9cole Polytechnique\n | access-date =December 4, 2018\n | quote = }}</ref>\n*2018 \u2013 [[Arthur L. Schawlow Prize in Laser Science]] by the [[American Physical Society]] <ref>{{cite web | title=Arthur L. Schawlow Prize in Laser Science | website=APS Physics &#124; APS Home | url=https://www.aps.org/programs/honors/prizes/schawlow.cfm | access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n*2018 \u2013 [[Nobel Prize in Physics]], together with [[Arthur Ashkin]] and [[Donna Strickland]]<ref name=\"PW\">{{cite web |title=Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland win the Nobel Prize for Physics |url=https://physicsworld.com/a/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-the-nobel-prize-for-physics/ |publisher=Physics World |accessdate=2 October 2018 |date=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n* 2020 \u2013 Honorary Doctorate of [[Vilnius University]]<ref>{{cite web\n | url =http://naujienos.vu.lt/nobelio-premijos-laureatui-gerardui-mourou-suteikiamas-vu-garbes-daktaro-vardas/\n | title =Nobel laureate G\u00e9rard Mourou is awarded the VU honorary doctorate (in Lithuanian)\n | date =February 3, 2020\n | website =\n | publisher =Vilnius university\n | access-date =February 5, 2020\n | quote = }}</ref>\n* 25 February 2020 \u2013 Honorary Doctorate of Bulgarian Academy of Sciences [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fY5UcvmSS4A&feature=youtu.be ceremony]\n\n==Writings==\n* {{cite book |last=Mourou |first=G\u00e9rard |editor1-last=Stroud |editor1-first=Carlos |title=A Jewel in the Crown: 75th Anniversary Essays of The Institute of Optics of the University of Rochester |date=2004 |publisher=Meliora Press |location=Rochester, NY |page=272 |chapter-url=http://www2.optics.rochester.edu/~stroud/BookHTML/ChapVI_pdf/VI_53.pdf |url=http://www2.optics.rochester.edu/~stroud/BookHTML/contents.htm |chapter=53. The dawn of ultrafast science and technology at the University of Rochester. |isbn=978-1580461627}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Scholia|author}}\n{{Commons category|G\u00e9rard Mourou}}\n*{{Google Scholar id | spudk8gAAAAJ }}\n*[http://loa.ensta.fr/index_gb.html Laboratoire d'Optique Appliquee]\n*[http://www.polytechnique.edu/ Ecole Polytechnique, Palaiseau]\n*[https://cuos.engin.umich.edu/ Center for Ultrafast Optical Science]\n\n{{Nobel Prize in Physics}}\n{{2018 Nobel Prize winners}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mourou, Gerard}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ard\u00e8che]]\n[[Category:French physicists]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan faculty]]\n[[Category:Nobel laureates in Physics]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:French Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:Laser researchers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Optical Society]]\n[[Category:Fellow Members of the IEEE]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Physical Society]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Pierre and Marie Curie University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = G\u00e9rard Mourou\n| image = Ecole polytechnique (44330870254).jpg\n| birth_name = G\u00e9rard Albert Mourou\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1944|6|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Albertville]], [[France]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| education = [[Universit\u00e9 Grenoble Alpes|University of Grenoble]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BSc]], [[Master of Science|MSc]])}}<br />[[Pierre and Marie Curie University]] {{small|([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n| thesis_title = \n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = \n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = [[Donna Strickland]]\n| notable_students = \n| known_for = [[Chirped pulse amplification]]\n| awards = [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] {{small|(2018)}}\n| workplaces = [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique|\u00c9cole polytechnique]]<br />[[ENSTA ParisTech]]<br />[[University of Rochester]]<br />[[University of Michigan]]\n}}\n\n'''G\u00e9rard Albert Mourou''' ({{IPA-fr|\u0292e\u0281a\u0281 mu\u0281u|lang}}; born 22 June 1944)<ref name=\"Lindinger\">{{cite news |last=Lindinger |first=Manfred |date=2 October 2018 |title=Eine Zange aus lauter Licht |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wissen/nobelpreise/physik-nobelpreis-2018-praezisionswerkzeuge-aus-laserlicht-15818493.html |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |language=German |accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Nobel\">{{cite web |date=5 October 2018 |title=G\u00e9rard Mourou \u2013 Facts \u2013 2018 |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/2018/mourou/facts/ |work=NobelPrize.org |publisher=Nobel Media AB |accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> is a French scientist and pioneer in the field of [[electrical engineering]] and [[lasers]].  He was awarded a [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] in 2018, along with [[Donna Strickland]], for the invention of [[chirped pulse amplification]], a technique later used to create ultrashort-pulse, very high-intensity ([[petawatt]]) laser pulses.<ref name=Michigan_Profile>{{cite web |url=http://www.engin.umich.edu/research/cuos/ResearchGroups/HFS/Profiles/Gerard_Mourou.html |title=G\u00e9rard Mourou |last= |first= |date=2 October 2018 |website= |publisher=University of Michigan | access-date = |quote=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905085848/http://www.engin.umich.edu/research/cuos/ResearchGroups/HFS/Profiles/Gerard_Mourou.html |archive-date=5 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Mourou and his team at the [[University of Michigan]] discovered that the balance between the self-focusing refraction (see [[Kerr effect]]) and self-attenuating [[diffraction]] by [[ionization]] and rarefaction of a laser beam of terawatt intensities in the atmosphere creates \"filaments\" which act as [[waveguide]]s for the beam thus preventing divergence.\n\n==Career==\nMourou has been director of the Laboratoire d'optique appliqu\u00e9e at the [[ENSTA]] from 2005 to 2009. He is a professor and member of Haut Coll\u00e8ge at the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique|\u00c9cole polytechnique]] and A. D. Moore Distinguished University Professor Emeritus at the [[University of Michigan]] where he has taught for over 16 years. He was the founding director of the Center for Ultrafast Optical Science at the University of Michigan in 1990. He had previously led a research group on ultrafast sciences at Laboratoire d'optique appliqu\u00e9e of ENSTA and \u00c9cole polytechnique, after obtaining a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degree from [[Pierre and Marie Curie University]] in 1973. He then went to the United States and became a professor at the [[University of Rochester]] in 1977, where he and his then student [[Donna Strickland]] produced their Nobel prize-winning work in the [[Laboratory for Laser Energetics]] at the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rochester.edu/newscenter/rochesters-breakthrough-in-laser-science-earns-nobel-prize-340302/ |title=Rochester breakthrough in laser science earns Nobel Prize |date=2 October 2018 |website=University of Rochester |accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref> The pair co-invented [[chirped pulse amplification]], a \"method of generating high-intensity, ultra-short optical pulses\".<ref name=\"bbc2\">{{cite news |last1=Murphy |first1=Jessica |title=Donna Strickland: The 'laser jock' Nobel prize winner |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45722890 |accessdate=2 October 2018 |publisher=BBC News |date=2 October 2018}}</ref> Strickland's doctoral thesis was on \"development of an ultra-bright laser and an application to multi-photon ionization\".<ref name=\"Thesis\">{{cite thesis |last=Strickland |first=Donna Theo |author-link=Donna Strickland |date=1988 |title=Development of an ultra-bright laser and an application to multi-photon ionization |type=PhD |publisher=University of Rochester |url=http://www.lle.rochester.edu/media/publications/documents/theses/Strickland.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707150743/http://www.lle.rochester.edu/media/publications/documents/theses/Strickland.pdf |archive-date=7 July 2013 |accessdate=6 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2000s, Mourou was featured by a French film company in a publicity video for the [[Extreme Light Infrastructure]] (ELI).<ref name=\"LeMonde\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/sciences/article/2018/10/02/quand-le-nobel-gerard-mourou-se-mettait-en-scene-dans-un-clip-musical-potache_5363583_1650684.html |title=Quand le Nobel G\u00e9rard Mourou se mettait en sc\u00e8ne dans un clip musical potache |last=Morin |first=Herv\u00e9 |work=Le Monde |quote=Le laboratoire avait contact\u00e9 une compagnie de th\u00e9\u00e2tre sp\u00e9cialis\u00e9e dans les sujets scientifiques..en 2008. C\u2019est \u00e0 cette occasion que <nowiki>[r\u00e9alisateur]</nowiki> Mokaddem Djemel a rencontr\u00e9 les chercheurs. De fil en aiguille, l\u2019id\u00e9e d\u2019une vid\u00e9o a germ\u00e9, utilisant une chanson du spectacle. (The lab contacted a theatre company specializing in scientific subjects..in 2008. It was then that <nowiki>[filmmaker]</nowiki> Mokaddem Djemel met the researchers. Gradually, the idea of a video was born, using a song from the show.) |date=2 October 2018 |accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Have you seen ELI3 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k6i7A8Plqb8 |last=|access-date=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 November 2015, he attended the Third Christmas Lecture held in Bucharest. His presentation was entitled ''Breaking Through The Unknown: Extreme light, Science to Art''. The previous lectures were given by Sir [[Thomas Kibble]] and [[Joseph Silk]].\n\n=== Nobel Prize ===\n[[File:Ecole polytechnique (31183345568).jpg|thumb|262px|Mourou, speaking in 2018 after being awarded the Nobel Prize]]\nOn 2 October 2018, Mourou and [[Donna Strickland|Strickland]] were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics, along with  for their joint work on [[chirped pulse amplification]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/oct/02/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-win-nobel-physics-prize |title=Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland win Nobel physics prize |first=Ian |last=Sample |date=2 October 2018 |journal=The Guardian |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> They shared half of the Prize, while the other half was awarded to [[Arthur Ashkin]] for his invention of \"optical tweezers that grab particles, atoms, viruses and other living cells with their laser beam fingers\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/arthur-ashkin-2-others-win-nobel-physics-prize-for-laser-research/ |title=Arthur Ashkin, 2 others win Nobel Physics Prize for laser research |date=2 October 2018 |website=Times of Israel |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"physicsworld.com\">{{cite web |url=https://physicsworld.com/a/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-the-nobel-prize-for-physics/ |title=Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland win the Nobel Prize for Physics \u2013 Physics World |date=2 October 2018 |publisher= |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:G\u00e9rard Mourou EM1B5793 (46234161551).jpg|thumb|262px|G\u00e9rard Mourou during Nobel press conference in Stockholm, December 2018]]\n\nMourou and Strickland found that stretching a laser out reduced its peak power, which could then be greatly amplified using normal instruments.\nIt could then be compressed to create the short-lived, highly powerful lasers they were after.<ref name=\"physicsworld.com\" /> The technique, which was described in Strickland's first scientific publication, came to be known as chirped pulse amplification (CPA). They were probably unaware at the time that their tools would make it possible to study natural phenomena in unprecedented ways.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://physicsworld.com/a/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-the-nobel-prize-for-physics/ |title=Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland win the Nobel Prize for Physics |first= |last= |date=2 October 2018 |publisher= |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> CPA could also per definition be used to create a laser pulse that only lasts one attosecond, one-billionth of a billionth of a second. At those timescales, it became possible not only to study chemical reactions, but what happens inside individual atoms.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' and [[Scientific American]] provided simplified summaries of the work of Strickland and Mourou: it \"paved the way for the shortest, most intense laser beams ever created\". \"The ultrabrief, ultrasharp beams can be used to make extremely precise cuts so their technique is now used in laser machining and enables doctors to perform millions of corrective\" [[laser eye surgery|laser eye surgeries]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Physics Nobel prize won by Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/oct/02/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-win-nobel-physics-prize |accessdate=2 October 2018 |publisher=The Guardian |date=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title='Optical Tweezers' and Tools Used for Laser Eye Surgery Snag Physics Nobel |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/optical-tweezers-and-tools-used-for-laser-eye-surgery-snag-physics-nobel1/ |accessdate=2 October 2018 |publisher=Scientific American |date=2 October 2018}}</ref> Canadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] acknowledged the achievements of Mourou and Strickland: \"Their innovative work can be found in applications including corrective eye surgery, and is expected to have a significant impact on cancer therapy and other physics research in the future\".<ref>[https://pm.gc.ca/eng/news/2018/10/02/statement-prime-minister-donna-strickland-winning-nobel-prize-physics Statement by the Prime Minister on Donna Strickland winning the Nobel Prize in Physics 2 October 2018 PMO]</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*1995 \u2013 R. W. Wood Prize by the [[Optical Society of America|OSA]]<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.osa.org/en-us/awards_and_grants/awards/award_description/rwwood/\n | title =R. W. Wood Prize\n | date =\n | website =\n | publisher =The Optical Society\n | access-date =\n | quote =For contributions to the field of ultrafast optics, in particular for introducing the concept of chirped pulse amplification for laser systems to boost optical power peaks to unprecedented levels  }}</ref>\n*1997 \u2013 SPIE Harold E. Edgerton Award<ref name=\"SPIE\">{{cite web |title=SPIE Harold E. Edgerton Award in High-Speed Optics |url=http://spie.org/about-spie/awards-programs/current-award-winners/spie-harold-e-edgerton-award-in-high-speed-optics?SSO=1 |website=spie.org |publisher=International Society for Optics and Photonics |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n*2004 \u2013 IEEE LEOS [[IEEE Photonics Society|Quantum Electronics Award]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.photonicssociety.org/awards/quantum-electronics-award/quantum-electronics-award-award-winners |title=Quantum Electronics Award Winners |website=IEEE Photonics Society |accessdate=2 October 2018|quote=For pioneering contributions to ultrafast optics including optical sampling and intense fs pulses}}</ref>\n*2005 \u2013 Willis E. Lamb Award for Laser Science and Quantum Optics<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambaward.org/2005/2005-mourou.html |title=G\u00e9rard Mourou \u2013 the 2005 Willis E. Lamb Award for Laser Science and Quantum Optics |website=www.lambaward.org |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n*2009 \u2013 [[Charles Hard Townes Award]] by the [[Optical Society of America|OSA]]<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.osa.org/en-us/history/biographies/gerard-mourou/\n | title =G\u00e9rard Mourou\n | date =\n | website =\n | publisher =The Optical Society\n | access-date =2018-10-12\n | quote = }}</ref>\n* 2016 \u2013 [[Frederic Ives Medal]]<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.polytechnique.edu/en/content/gerard-mourou-receives-frederic-ives-medal-optical-society-america\n | title =G\u00e9rard Mourou receives the Frederic Ives Medal of the Optical Society of America\n | date =March 30, 2016\n | website =\n | publisher =\u00c9cole Polytechnique\n | access-date =December 4, 2018\n | quote = }}</ref>\n*2018 \u2013 [[Arthur L. Schawlow Prize in Laser Science]] by the [[American Physical Society]] <ref>{{cite web | title=Arthur L. Schawlow Prize in Laser Science | website=APS Physics &#124; APS Home | url=https://www.aps.org/programs/honors/prizes/schawlow.cfm | access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n*2018 \u2013 [[Nobel Prize in Physics]], together with [[Arthur Ashkin]] and [[Donna Strickland]]<ref name=\"PW\">{{cite web |title=Arthur Ashkin, G\u00e9rard Mourou and Donna Strickland win the Nobel Prize for Physics |url=https://physicsworld.com/a/arthur-ashkin-gerard-mourou-and-donna-strickland-the-nobel-prize-for-physics/ |publisher=Physics World |accessdate=2 October 2018 |date=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n* 2020 \u2013 Honorary Doctorate of [[Vilnius University]]<ref>{{cite web\n | url =http://naujienos.vu.lt/nobelio-premijos-laureatui-gerardui-mourou-suteikiamas-vu-garbes-daktaro-vardas/\n | title =Nobel laureate G\u00e9rard Mourou is awarded the VU honorary doctorate (in Lithuanian)\n | date =February 3, 2020\n | website =\n | publisher =Vilnius university\n | access-date =February 5, 2020\n | quote = }}</ref>\n* 25 February 2020 - Honorary Doctorate of Bulgarian Academy of Sciences [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fY5UcvmSS4A&feature=youtu.be ceremony]\n\n==Writings==\n* {{cite book |last=Mourou |first=G\u00e9rard |editor1-last=Stroud |editor1-first=Carlos |title=A Jewel in the Crown: 75th Anniversary Essays of The Institute of Optics of the University of Rochester |date=2004 |publisher=Meliora Press |location=Rochester, NY |page=272 |chapter-url=http://www2.optics.rochester.edu/~stroud/BookHTML/ChapVI_pdf/VI_53.pdf |url=http://www2.optics.rochester.edu/~stroud/BookHTML/contents.htm |chapter=53. The dawn of ultrafast science and technology at the University of Rochester. |isbn=978-1580461627}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Scholia|author}}\n{{Commons category|G\u00e9rard Mourou}}\n*{{Google Scholar id | spudk8gAAAAJ }}\n*[http://loa.ensta.fr/index_gb.html Laboratoire d'Optique Appliquee]\n*[http://www.polytechnique.edu/ Ecole Polytechnique, Palaiseau]\n*[https://cuos.engin.umich.edu/ Center for Ultrafast Optical Science]\n\n{{Nobel Prize in Physics}}\n{{2018 Nobel Prize winners}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mourou, Gerard}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ard\u00e8che]]\n[[Category:French physicists]]\n[[Category: